<!doctype html><html lang="en"><head><meta charset="utf-8"><meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1"><title>120-Day Entry Plan | Universal Orlando AI Technology</title><link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css"></head><body class="document-body"><nav class="document-nav no-print"><a class="nav-name" href="index.html">Russell Dudek <span>/ Candidate Vision</span></a><div class="doc-actions"><a class="btn primary" href="docs/Russell-Dudek-Universal-Orlando-AI-120-Day-Plan.pdf" download>Download PDF</a><button class="btn" onclick="window.print()">Print</button></div></nav><main class="document-shell"><section class="report-page report-title"><div class="report-inner"><div class="report-lockup"><img src="assets/brand/universal-orlando-logo.png" alt="Universal Orlando Resort"><span class="report-label">Independent candidate brief by Russell Dudek</span></div><h1>First 120 Days</h1><p class="deck">A discovery-led entry plan for the Director, Artificial Intelligence Technology opportunity.</p><div class="thesis">Read the show. Name the contracts. Prove one run. Compound the learning.</div><footer class="page-footer"><span>Russell Dudek | 120-day entry plan</span><span>1</span></footer></div></section>
<section class="report-page"><div class="report-inner"><header class="report-header"><h1>Days 1-30 | Read the show</h1><img src="assets/brand/universal-orlando-logo.png" alt="Universal Orlando Resort"></header><section class="report-section"><h2>Objective</h2><p>Build trust and a fact base before prescribing architecture or reorganizing work.</p><div class="report-grid-2"><div class="report-card"><h3>Strategy and portfolio</h3><p>Clarify executive goals, current AI inventory, spend, use-case intake, decision rights, benefits and stopped work.</p></div><div class="report-card"><h3>Architecture and data</h3><p>Map platforms, pipelines, model environments, identity, observability, privacy/security boundaries and critical technical debt.</p></div><div class="report-card"><h3>People and partners</h3><p>Understand team capability, staffing gaps, product and operations relationships, vendors, API dependencies and ownership seams.</p></div><div class="report-card"><h3>Frontline reality</h3><p>Observe selected guest, park, hotel, service and enterprise workflows; capture friction, exceptions and existing workarounds.</p></div></div><h2>Deliverables</h2><ul><li>AI portfolio and dependency map.</li><li>Stakeholder and decision-rights map.</li><li>Initial technical risk and opportunity register.</li><li>Candidate list of 3-5 bounded workflows for deeper discovery.</li><li>Agreed operating cadence with executive sponsor and peer leaders.</li></ul><h2>Listening route</h2><table class="phase-table"><tr><th>Stakeholder</th><th>Question to resolve</th></tr><tr><td>Executive sponsors</td><td>Which outcomes matter enough to fund, sequence or stop work?</td></tr><tr><td>Park, hotel and enterprise operators</td><td>Where do exceptions, handoffs and workarounds create avoidable friction?</td></tr><tr><td>Data, ML and platform teams</td><td>Where are architecture, data quality, deployment and observability strongest or weakest?</td></tr><tr><td>Cyber, privacy, legal and EHS</td><td>Which consequences and controls change the acceptable technical design?</td></tr><tr><td>Vendors and product partners</td><td>Where is acceleration useful, and where has ownership become ambiguous?</td></tr></table><h2>Do not do yet</h2><p>Do not announce a generic platform, promise enterprise ROI, or treat an attractive demo as a production candidate before owners and operating conditions are known.</p></section><footer class="page-footer"><span>Russell Dudek | 120-day entry plan</span><span>2</span></footer></div></section>
<section class="report-page"><div class="report-inner"><header class="report-header"><h1>Days 31-60 | Name the contracts</h1><img src="assets/brand/universal-orlando-logo.png" alt="Universal Orlando Resort"></header><section class="report-section"><h2>Objective</h2><p>Create a common language for prioritization, production readiness and accountability without centralizing every domain decision.</p><h2>Mechanisms to establish</h2><table class="phase-table"><tr><th>Mechanism</th><th>Purpose</th><th>First output</th></tr><tr><td>Portfolio intake and triage</td><td>Compare value, feasibility, data readiness, consequence, adoption burden and reuse.</td><td>Transparent prioritized portfolio.</td></tr><tr><td>AI Show Contract</td><td>Align Scene, Cue, Run and Review before production.</td><td>One-page contract per candidate service.</td></tr><tr><td>Risk-tiered review</td><td>Match governance and test depth to consequence.</td><td>Defined release authorities and evidence.</td></tr><tr><td>Technical standards</td><td>Clarify data, model, MLOps, security, observability, rollback and API requirements.</td><td>Minimum production pattern and exception path.</td></tr><tr><td>Executive scorecard</td><td>Report outcome, run-state, trust, adoption and economics together.</td><td>Monthly portfolio review.</td></tr></table><h2>Team agenda</h2><ul><li>Define responsibilities across ML engineering, data science, data engineering, platform, product, cyber, privacy and business ownership.</li><li>Identify recruiting priorities and succession or development opportunities.</li><li>Set expectations for technical reviews, coaching, documentation and incident learning.</li></ul><h2>Decision rights to make explicit</h2><div class="report-grid-2"><div class="report-card"><h3>Business owner</h3><p>Outcome, workflow change, adoption and benefit realization.</p></div><div class="report-card"><h3>Technical owner</h3><p>Architecture, model, platform, service health and recovery.</p></div><div class="report-card"><h3>Control authorities</h3><p>Security, privacy, legal, risk and consequence-tier requirements.</p></div><div class="report-card"><h3>Release authority</h3><p>Who can release, constrain, hold, roll back or retire the service.</p></div></div></section><footer class="page-footer"><span>Russell Dudek | 120-day entry plan</span><span>3</span></footer></div></section>
